"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody. An interesting point that Albert Howard made in his works was that colonialism at least partially occurred because of the infertility of European soils to support their population. European farming was mostly done from a slash and burn agricultural standpoint where forests were cut down, slashed and burnt, and then the fertile ground underneath had been created from this forest constantly feeding organic material into the ground was used for production crops until the land was no longer sufficient for that, and then they would move on and cut down another chunk. And this is a great way to support a population, but it quickly used up the forests of Europe, and what happened was that there was too many people for too poor soil. And that big part of colonialism was to set up plantations all over the world and mine native soils for the fertility to support European crops. This is an interesting way of looking at it because eventually these soils also become uh infertile or less fertile because you mined out a lot of the organic matter, which happens when you're doing this uh production that doesn't have any sort of recontribution to the organic matter in the soil. So you just basically use it up. And what happens is that over a period of time you you find that the reaction to the soil is to compact and that locks out nitrogen. The nitrogen from the atmosphere no longer goes in it, the legumes no longer replenish it, and you start seeing nitrogen deficiencies everywhere. And so there is this great uh search for mostly bird dung to get its nitrogen value until the nitrogen pellet came about in the 50s, where or a little bit before that, where they finally chemically put nitrogen into a uh pellet fertilizer. Uh first they used it for bombs, but then they used it for fertilizers. But the the gist of this is that we have worked a system from time and world that's that's not functioning correctly. We need to have a system that contributes to the organic matter in the soil and not just depletes it to add chemicals. Chemical fertilizers have locked out the biology in the soil. And if you go to any cultivated areas that where it's been plowed and fertilized and pesticides have been used and even when they haven't it's been an organic farm, you'll try to find the the living element the soil and you're sift through it and you'll just find particulate matter there's almost nothing in it. And I I've looked around a lot of these soils and it's it's very interesting to see no earthworms, no beetles, nothing crawling and beyond that nothing too much living outside of you know even in at the microscopic level. Anyway, I want to give this quick video uh talking about that because it's a real interesting concept that a lot of our history has been shaped by the lack of fertility in our soils and the need for more fertility uh with and how this has shaped our histories. Anyway thanks\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 0.24,\n      \"end\": 1.28,\n      \"duration\": 1.04,\n      \"confidence\": 0.986,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 0.24,\n          \"end\": 0.4,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.985\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 0.4,\n          \"end\": 0.56,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.999\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.64,\n          \"end\": 0.8,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 0.8,\n          \"end\": 0.96,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 0.96,\n          \"end\": 1.12,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n       